1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,820
Now we're going to transition into how we work with numbers in strings in Python.

2

00:00:04,820  -->  00:00:07,160
The first stop is integers.

3

00:00:07,160  -->  00:00:08,740
These are whole numbers,

4

00:00:08,740  -->  00:00:12,560
both positive and negative without any decimal points.

5

00:00:12,560  -->  00:00:15,640
Think about counting objects like apples or cars.

6

00:00:15,640  -->  00:00:19,540
If you're counting the cars in a lot or apples in an orchard,

7

00:00:19,540  -->  00:00:21,960
this doesn't include decimals or fractions.

8

00:00:21,960  -->  00:00:25,160
We only care about whole apples and whole cars.

9

00:00:25,160  -->  00:00:27,660
Another great example is counting time,

10

00:00:27,660  -->  00:00:32,180
such as watch time when you're streaming a movie or TV show.

11

00:00:32,180  -->  00:00:35,520
When considering minutes watched or hours watched,

12

00:00:35,520  -->  00:00:38,800
you're only interested in the whole number in this case.

13

00:00:38,800  -->  00:00:42,020
When you think about integers, think counting numbers.

14

00:00:42,020  -->  00:00:46,220
Some examples of integers can look like this with age, year, cars,

15

00:00:46,220  -->  00:00:51,450
and books, and notice the lack of comma where we define the integer of books.

16

00:00:51,450  -->  00:00:55,640
We don't need to worry about commas when we define our integers in Python.

17

00:00:55,640  -->  00:01:00,345
These data types are numbers and do contain decimals.

18

00:01:00,345  -->  00:01:03,990
They are used to represent values that are not whole numbers,

19

00:01:03,990  -->  00:01:06,290
such as measurements or prices.

20

00:01:06,290  -->  00:01:08,770
When purchasing a coffee at your local store,

21

00:01:08,770  -->  00:01:11,970
and you see the price at $4.99,

22

00:01:11,970  -->  00:01:14,015
that is a floating point number.

23

00:01:14,015  -->  00:01:17,620
Something important to note is that Python default to

24

00:01:17,620  -->  00:01:21,500
the integer type when you write a whole number without a decimal point,

25

00:01:21,500  -->  00:01:24,320
and to the floating point type,

26

00:01:24,320  -->  00:01:26,120
when you include a decimal point,

27

00:01:26,120  -->  00:01:29,540
even if the number is a whole number like 5.0.

28

00:01:29,540  -->  00:01:32,500
In Python, when you work with numbers, the type,

29

00:01:32,500  -->  00:01:34,640
whether it's an integer or a floating point,

30

00:01:34,640  -->  00:01:36,900
depends on how the number is written.

31

00:01:36,900  -->  00:01:40,720
Integers are whole numbers without a decimal point.

32

00:01:40,720  -->  00:01:42,760
For example, 5 is an integer.

33

00:01:42,760  -->  00:01:46,000
Floating point numbers are numbers with a decimal point.

34

00:01:46,000  -->  00:01:49,980
For example, 5.0 is a floating point number.

35

00:01:49,980  -->  00:01:54,030
Also, something tricky to note is that floats can be negative.

36

00:01:54,030  -->  00:01:59,410
Here are a few more examples of floats with price, temperature, and length.

37

00:01:59,410  -->  00:02:04,830
Scientific notation represents very large or small numbers to the power of 10.

38

00:02:04,830  -->  00:02:07,150
Take, for example, 1 million.

39

00:02:07,150  -->  00:02:09,730
That is a one with six zeros.

40

00:02:09,730  -->  00:02:13,590
In scientific notation, that would be 1*10^6.

41

00:02:13,590  -->  00:02:20,490
In Python, a lower case E is used to signify the 10 to the power of.

42

00:02:20,490  -->  00:02:24,580
In our example, this would be 1e6.

43

00:02:24,580  -->  00:02:27,520
These numbers can be negative as well,

44

00:02:27,520  -->  00:02:37,130
0.0004 would be written as 4*10^(-4) or 4e(-4).

45

00:02:37,130  -->  00:02:46,160
Quick note, 0.0004 is the same as 0.0004 in Python.

46

00:02:46,160  -->  00:02:50,360
You've already been using strings in this course, if you can believe it.

47

00:02:50,360  -->  00:02:53,960
Strings are sequences of characters used to store text.

48

00:02:53,960  -->  00:02:58,010
For instance, first_name=Alice.

49

00:02:58,010  -->  00:03:00,760
They can be enclosed in single quotes,

50

00:03:00,760  -->  00:03:04,530
double quotes or triple quotes for multi line text,

51

00:03:04,530  -->  00:03:08,960
so whether we are setting something equal to something else in quotation marks,

52

00:03:08,960  -->  00:03:12,570
that is what we call setting a variable as a string.

53

00:03:12,570  -->  00:03:14,145
When you see these examples,

54

00:03:14,145  -->  00:03:16,760
you'll go, oh, yes, I remember seeing this.

55

00:03:16,760  -->  00:03:18,860
That seems pretty familiar.

56

00:03:18,860  -->  00:03:23,220
You probably have seen these messages in applications you use or software you download.

57

00:03:23,220  -->  00:03:28,290
Log in successful, software upgraded to the latest version x.xx.

58

00:03:28,290  -->  00:03:31,740
Whether you see these types of messages of text or characters,

59

00:03:31,740  -->  00:03:34,140
remember that these are strings.

60

00:03:34,140  -->  00:03:36,060
Since this is Python, after all,

61

00:03:36,060  -->  00:03:39,110
there are methods to write machine readable code.

62

00:03:39,110  -->  00:03:41,620
Up until this point, we've been going through a lot of

63

00:03:41,620  -->  00:03:46,600
human readable code methods that help us write the code that we need Python to perform.

64

00:03:46,600  -->  00:03:48,400
But there are ways to define

65

00:03:48,400  -->  00:03:52,080
machine readable code that Python will understand at the byte level.

66

00:03:52,080  -->  00:03:55,520
These are different ways to represent numbers in various bases.

67

00:03:55,520  -->  00:03:57,120
Let's go through some of them.

68

00:03:57,120  -->  00:04:01,100
With binary, this method uses digits 0 and 1,

69

00:04:01,100  -->  00:04:06,460
prefixed with 0b, such as binary_value=0b1010.

70

00:04:09,020  -->  00:04:12,580
This is binary speak for 10 in decimal.

71

00:04:12,580  -->  00:04:16,865
With octal, this method uses digits 0-7,

72

00:04:16,865  -->  00:04:22,900
prefixed with 0o, such as octal_value=0o12.

73

00:04:25,000  -->  00:04:28,820
This is octal speak for 10 in decimal,

74

00:04:28,820  -->  00:04:31,700
and of course, decimal base 10.

75

00:04:31,700  -->  00:04:34,620
This is the standard number system we use

76

00:04:34,620  -->  00:04:38,140
every day and one that I'm sure you'll recognize.

77

00:04:38,140  -->  00:04:41,780
Remember, this data type is, what do we call it?

78

00:04:41,780  -->  00:04:43,680
That's right, an integer,

79

00:04:43,680  -->  00:04:47,175
such as decimal underscore value equals 10,

80

00:04:47,175  -->  00:04:49,560
and of course, that means ten.

81

00:04:49,560  -->  00:04:52,930
Hexadecimal, base 16 is a method that uses digits

82

00:04:52,930  -->  00:04:56,750
0-9 and letters A to F, prefixed with 0x.

83

00:04:56,750  -->  00:04:59,220
If you've ever seen block chain or crypto wallets,

84

00:04:59,220  -->  00:05:03,640
you might see something like this where the wallet has a 0x...,

85

00:05:03,640  -->  00:05:06,620
followed by a series of random characters,

86

00:05:06,620  -->  00:05:10,300
or you might see hashes that start with Saw 256,

87

00:05:10,300  -->  00:05:11,880
which is an encryption algorithm,

88

00:05:11,880  -->  00:05:16,660
and that leverages hexadecimal numbers to represent values that a computer program

89

00:05:16,660  -->  00:05:22,840
can understand easily and efficiently, such as hex_value=0xA.

90

00:05:23,470  -->  00:05:27,390
This is hexadecimal speak for ten decimal.

91

00:05:27,390  -->  00:05:30,480
It's okay if you don't fully grasp these concepts right now.

92

00:05:30,480  -->  00:05:35,000
The goal here is just to introduce you to these numeral systems,

93

00:05:35,000  -->  00:05:37,160
not to necessarily master them at this point.

94

00:05:37,160  -->  00:05:39,100
As you continue learning and practicing,

95

00:05:39,100  -->  00:05:41,485
these ideas will become much clearer.

96

00:05:41,485  -->  00:05:44,310
If binary octal, decimal,

97

00:05:44,310  -->  00:05:47,880
and hexadecimal seems confusing to you, don't stress out.

98

00:05:47,880  -->  00:05:50,500
This is something that you will gain exposure to

99

00:05:50,500  -->  00:05:54,040
if and when you begin programming with these various systems.

100

00:05:54,040  -->  00:05:55,600
For the PCP exam,

101

00:05:55,600  -->  00:06:01,020
just make sure that you are aware that they exist and what the value looks like.
